&lt;p&gt;The erroneous part is &lt;strong&gt;&amp;#39;The company offered discounts low as&amp;#39;.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The error lies in the incorrect structure of the phrase &lt;strong&gt;&amp;quot;discounts low as.&amp;quot;&lt;/strong&gt; The correct phrase should be &lt;strong&gt;&amp;quot;discounts as low as.&amp;quot;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The expression &lt;strong&gt;&amp;quot;as low as&amp;quot; &lt;/strong&gt;is&lt;strong&gt; a comparative phrase&lt;/strong&gt; used to denote &lt;strong&gt;the minimum or lowest level of something&lt;/strong&gt;. It&amp;#39;s commonly used to emphasize a particularly &lt;strong&gt;low price or rate.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;In the &lt;strong&gt;context&lt;/strong&gt; of the sentence, &lt;strong&gt;the company was offering discounts&lt;/strong&gt;, and the sentence aimed to highlight the extent of these discounts, specifying that they were &lt;strong&gt;as low as&lt;/strong&gt; &lt;strong&gt;twenty-five percent.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Therefore, to properly convey this meaning, it&amp;#39;s essential to use the phrase &lt;strong&gt;&amp;quot;as low as&amp;quot;&lt;/strong&gt; to correctly indicate the degree or level of the discounts offered by the company.&lt;br /&gt;
	&amp;nbsp;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;Correct Sentence:&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;strong&gt;The company offered discounts as low as&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;nbsp;twenty-five percent on selected products, aiming to attract a broader customer base and encourage greater sales during the festive season.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;The correct answer is &lt;strong&gt;Option 3&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;The primary issue in the sentence is the unnecessary repetition of the preposition &amp;quot;&lt;strong&gt;to&lt;/strong&gt;.&amp;quot; &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;The correct sentence should use either &amp;quot;&lt;strong&gt;whom it belonged to&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;quot; or &amp;quot;&lt;strong&gt;to whom it belonged&lt;/strong&gt;,&amp;quot; but not both.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;The correct phrase should be &amp;quot;&lt;strong&gt;to whom it belonged&lt;/strong&gt;,&amp;quot; ensuring grammatical correctness and clarity.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;Thus, the error is located in &lt;strong&gt;part 3&lt;/strong&gt; of the sentence.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;Therefore, the correct answer is &lt;strong&gt;3&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Correct Sentence:&lt;/strong&gt; &lt;em&gt;&amp;quot;I found this toy while digging in the garden, but I don&amp;rsquo;t know to whom it belonged.&amp;quot;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;1: &amp;quot;I found this toy&amp;quot;&lt;/strong&gt; &amp;ndash; This part of the sentence is grammatically correct and does not require any changes.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;2: &amp;quot;while digging in the garden, but&amp;quot;&lt;/strong&gt; &amp;ndash; This part of the sentence is grammatically correct and does not require any changes.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;3: &amp;quot;I don&amp;rsquo;t know to whom it belonged to&amp;quot;&lt;/strong&gt; &amp;ndash; This part of the sentence is grammatically incorrect due to the repetition of the preposition &amp;quot;to.&amp;quot;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p style=&quot;&quot;&gt;The correct answer is&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&amp;#39;3&amp;#39;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;i.e.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;strong&gt;process,&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;increasing transparency for middle-income earners&lt;/span&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul style=&quot;&quot;&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The sentence contains a list of objectives using parallel structure. The list should follow consistent grammatical structure.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;In this case, the list includes &amp;quot;simplify the filing process,&amp;quot; &amp;quot;eliminating loopholes,&amp;quot; and &amp;quot;increasing transparency.&amp;quot; The first and third objectives are inconsistent in form.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The correct parallel structure would be: &lt;strong&gt;&amp;quot;to simplify the filing process,&amp;quot; &amp;quot;to increase transparency,&amp;quot;&lt;/strong&gt; and &lt;strong&gt;&amp;quot;to eliminate loopholes.&amp;quot;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;Correct sentence:&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;em&gt;While the committee&amp;rsquo;s proposal to overhaul the tax code was met with significant skepticism, their primary objectives remain to simplify the filing process, to increase transparency for middle-income earners, and to eliminate loopholes that benefit multinational corporations.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Parallel Structure:&lt;/strong&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Ensures consistency when listing ideas, actions, or objectives.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Example: &amp;quot;She likes reading, swimming, and cycling.&amp;quot; (Correct)&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Example: &amp;quot;She likes reading, to swim, and cycling.&amp;quot; (Incorrect)&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Common Errors:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Using mixed forms like gerunds, infinitives, or base verbs within the same list.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Not aligning the grammatical structure across the items listed.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p style=&quot;&quot;&gt;The correct answer is&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&amp;#39;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Precedes before&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&amp;#39; i.e. this part of the sentence has an error&lt;/span&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;background-color: transparent; font-weight: 700; font-variant-numeric: normal; font-variant-east-asian: normal; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul style=&quot;&quot;&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;In the second part of the given sentence, the use of the&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;preposition &amp;#39;before&amp;#39;&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;is&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;superfluous or not required&lt;/span&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The givens sentence is talking about &lt;strong&gt;someone&amp;#39;s name before another person on the list&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The &lt;strong&gt;verb &amp;#39;precedes&amp;#39;&lt;/strong&gt; means&amp;nbsp;&lt;strong&gt;To be or go before something or someone&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;strong&gt;, as in place, order, rank, importance, or time&lt;/strong&gt;.
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Example:&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;em&gt;A major &lt;strong&gt;precedes&lt;/strong&gt; a captain in rank&lt;/em&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Therefore, the use of the &lt;strong&gt;preposition &amp;#39;before&amp;#39;&lt;/strong&gt; in the sentence is &lt;strong&gt;superfluous&lt;/strong&gt; and &lt;strong&gt;should be removed&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;br /&gt;
	&amp;nbsp;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p style=&quot;&quot;&gt;Hence, the correct answer is&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;option 4&lt;/span&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;Correct Sentence&lt;/span&gt;:&amp;nbsp;&lt;em&gt;Your name &lt;strong&gt;precedes&lt;/strong&gt; mine&amp;nbsp;in the list&lt;/em&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;The correct answer is &lt;strong&gt;Option 1&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;The sentence contains a grammatical inconsistency with the verb &amp;quot;&lt;strong&gt;come&lt;/strong&gt;.&amp;quot;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;The subject &amp;quot;&lt;strong&gt;None of them&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;quot; is singular and requires a singular verb in past tense.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;The verb &amp;quot;&lt;strong&gt;come&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;quot; should be replaced with &amp;quot;&lt;strong&gt;came&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;quot; to match the tense of the sentence.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;Thus, the error lies in &lt;strong&gt;Option 1&lt;/strong&gt;, &amp;quot;&lt;strong&gt;come to the&lt;/strong&gt;.&amp;quot;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;Therefore, the correct answer is &lt;strong&gt;Option 1&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Correct Sentence:&lt;/strong&gt; &lt;em&gt;&amp;quot;None of them &lt;strong&gt;came&amp;nbsp;&lt;/strong&gt;to the inauguration of our new factory.&amp;quot;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The part that is grammatically incorrect is &amp;#39;&lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;a essayist&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;.&amp;#39;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The sentence contains an error in the &lt;strong&gt;usage of article&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;We use &lt;strong&gt;a&lt;/strong&gt; before a singular noun beginning with a consonant sound&lt;strong&gt; &lt;/strong&gt;and&lt;strong&gt; an&lt;/strong&gt; before a singular noun beginning with a vowel sound.
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;For example, &lt;em&gt;a novel, a book, a car, a&amp;nbsp; pen, a dog &lt;/em&gt;but an apple, an essay, an owl, an underground tunnel etc.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;So, the correct sentence will be, &lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;Charles Dickens is famous as a novelist and an essayist.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Hence, the correct answer is &lt;strong&gt;Option 4&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/confusion-points-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Confusion Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Some might think that as Charles Dickens lived in the 19th century, the sentence should get a past verb, but this sentence has been framed to represent permanent truth. Therefore, it is not incorrect to use Simple present.
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;For example, &lt;em&gt;Rabindranath Tagore is one of the the best writer our country has ever produced&lt;/em&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is &amp;#39;&lt;strong&gt;C&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;#39;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;In part &amp;#39;C&amp;#39; of the given statement, the error is in the incorrect usage of the verb form of &amp;#39;cause&amp;#39;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Upon reading the complete sentence, we realize that &amp;#39;&lt;strong&gt;cause&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;#39; must be used as a &lt;strong&gt;gerund&lt;/strong&gt;, i.e. in its &amp;#39;&lt;strong&gt;-ing&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;#39;&amp;nbsp; form as it is acting as a &lt;strong&gt;transitive verb&lt;/strong&gt; and the meaning of the sentence is clear only when an &lt;strong&gt;object &lt;/strong&gt;i.e. &amp;#39;&lt;strong&gt;heartbreak&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;#39; comes in the sentence.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Therefore, the correct sentence will be:&lt;/strong&gt; &amp;#39;That Brutus, who was his trusted friend had attacked on him &lt;b&gt;causing&amp;nbsp;&lt;/b&gt;heartbreak to Julius Caesar&amp;#39;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Hence,&lt;strong&gt; option 3&lt;/strong&gt; is the correct answer.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;A &lt;strong&gt;gerund &lt;/strong&gt;is when a verb that acts as a noun.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;One of the ways is when the verb is used as a noun in the form of gerund i.e. is in its &amp;#39;-ing- form.
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;For eg.-&lt;/strong&gt; We give &lt;strong&gt;swimming &lt;/strong&gt;lessons during summers.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;span style=&quot;font-family: var(--bs-body-font-family); font-size: var(--bs-body-font-size); font-weight: var(--bs-body-font-weight); text-align: var(--bs-body-text-align);&quot;&gt;The correct answer is &lt;/span&gt;&lt;strong style=&quot;font-family: var(--bs-body-font-family); font-size: var(--bs-body-font-size); text-align: var(--bs-body-text-align);&quot;&gt;Option 1&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-family: var(--bs-body-font-family); font-size: var(--bs-body-font-size); font-weight: var(--bs-body-font-weight); text-align: var(--bs-body-text-align);&quot;&gt;.&lt;/span&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;The primary issue in the sentence is the use of &amp;quot;&lt;strong&gt;the loud&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;quot; instead of the correct comparative form &amp;quot;&lt;strong&gt;the loudest&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;quot;.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;In English, superlative forms are used to describe the highest degree of a quality among three or more items.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;The correct phrase should be &amp;quot;&lt;strong&gt;the loudest&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;quot;, ensuring grammatical correctness and clarity.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;Thus, the error is located in &lt;strong&gt;part 1&lt;/strong&gt; of the sentence.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;Therefore, the correct answer is &lt;strong&gt;Option 1&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Correct Sentence:&lt;/strong&gt; &lt;em&gt;&amp;quot;The smallest dog barks the loudest.&amp;quot;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;2: &amp;quot;The smallest&amp;quot;&lt;/strong&gt; &amp;ndash; This part of the sentence is grammatically correct and does not require any changes.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;3: &amp;quot;dog barks&amp;quot;&lt;/strong&gt; &amp;ndash; This part of the sentence is grammatically correct and does not require any changes.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;4: &amp;quot;No error&amp;quot;&lt;/strong&gt; &amp;ndash; This would be the correct option if there were no mistakes in the sentence, but there is an error in part 1.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p style=&quot;&quot;&gt;The erroneous part of the sentence is:&amp;nbsp;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;Make all decisions.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul style=&quot;&quot;&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Replace &amp;quot;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;make&lt;/span&gt;&amp;quot; with &amp;quot;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;makes&lt;/span&gt;&amp;quot; to correct the sentence.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The error here lies in the&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;Subject-Verb agreement&lt;/span&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The basic rule states that a singular subject takes a singular verb while a plural subject takes a plural verb.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Make &lt;/strong&gt;is used after a plural subject.
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;em&gt;They &lt;strong&gt;make &lt;/strong&gt;her realize the mistakes she made.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Makes &lt;/strong&gt;is used after a singular subject.
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;em&gt;She &lt;strong&gt;makes &lt;/strong&gt;mistakes.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The use of the plural verb form &amp;quot;&lt;strong&gt;make&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;quot; is incorrect in this sentence, as the subject, &amp;quot;&lt;strong&gt;The leader&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;quot; is a singular noun.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;A subject and verb must always be in agreement, meaning the verb needs to be changed to a singular form.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Therefore, &amp;quot;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;makes&lt;/span&gt;&amp;quot; should be used in the given sentence.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p style=&quot;&quot;&gt;Hence, the correct answer is&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;option 1&lt;/span&gt;, which contains an error.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;Corrected sentence:&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;em&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;The leader of the football players &lt;strong&gt;makes &lt;/strong&gt;all decisions for the entire group.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The erroneous part of the sentence is:&amp;nbsp;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;There are three cupholders placed&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;u style=&quot;&quot;&gt;on the cupboards&lt;/u&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;of the secretariat table.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;The error here lies in the use of preposition.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;Replace &amp;quot;&lt;strong&gt;on&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;quot; with &amp;quot;&lt;strong&gt;in&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;quot; to correct the sentence.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&amp;quot;&lt;strong&gt;IN&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;quot; is used when something is located inside of a defined space.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&amp;quot;&lt;strong&gt;ON&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;quot; is used when something is touching the surface of something.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&amp;quot;&lt;strong&gt;In the cupboards&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;quot;&amp;nbsp;is correct when we want to see what the cupboards contain.
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;For example-&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;em&gt;Take a look in the cupboard and see if there are any cans of soup there.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;em&gt;​&lt;/em&gt;Therefore, the underlined portion of option 2&amp;nbsp;contains a grammatical error.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Hence, the correct answer is &lt;strong&gt;option 2&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Corrected sentence&lt;/strong&gt;:&amp;nbsp;&lt;em&gt;There are three cupholders placed &lt;u&gt;in the cupboards&lt;/u&gt; of the secretariat table.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
